@startuml level-4f-code-procmonitor
!include https://raw.githubusercontent.com/plantuml-stdlib/C4-PlantUML/master/C4_Component.puml

title JOTP Code Level: ProcMonitor - Unilateral Monitoring

HIDE_STEREOTYPE()

Container_Boundary(api, "ProcMonitor Static Utility API") {
  Component(monitor_method, "static <S,M> MonitorRef<S,M> monitor(\n  Proc<S,M> target,\n  Consumer<Throwable> downHandler)", "Core Method", "Start unilateral monitoring\nWhen target terminates, invoke handler")

  Component(demonitor_method, "static void demonitor(MonitorRef ref)", "Method", "Stop monitoring\nHandler will not be invoked")

  Component(monitor_ref_record, "record MonitorRef<S,M>(\n  Proc<S,M> target,\n  Consumer<Throwable> callback)", "Handle", "Opaque monitor reference\nPassed to demonitor()")
}

Container_Boundary(implementation, "Implementation") {
  note right
  **monitor(target, handler) flow:**

  1. target.addTerminationCallback(handler)
  2. Return new MonitorRef(target, handler)

  Callbacks stored in target.terminationCallbacks list

  **demonitor(ref) flow:**

  1. ref.target().removeTerminationCallback(ref.callback())
  2. Removes handler from list
  end note
}

Container_Boundary(termination_flow, "Termination Callback Delivery") {
  Component(step1, "Target process terminates", "Event", "Normal or abnormal exit")

  Component(step2, "For each Watcher in terminationCallbacks", "Loop", "Iterate all monitoring callbacks")

  Component(step3, "Invoke handler(reason)", "Action", "reason = null (normal)\nor lastError (crash)")

  Component(step4, "Continue loop", "Next", "All handlers get notified\nEven if one throws")

  Rel(step1, step2, "triggers")
  Rel(step2, step3, "invokes")
  Rel(step3, step4, "next")
}

Container_Boundary(vs_link, "Contrast: Monitor vs Link") {
  note bottom
  **ProcLink (Bilateral)**
  - A.link(B) ← Both add crash callbacks
  - A crashes → B gets exit signal
  - B crashes → A gets exit signal
  - Both processes die (if not trapExits)

  **ProcMonitor (Unilateral)**
  - ProcMonitor.monitor(target, handler)
  - target terminates → handler invoked
  - Monitor never dies when target dies
  - No signal delivery to target

  **Use Cases**

  Links: Dependency between peers
  - A worker + a logger both linked
  - Either crashes → both die

  Monitor: Observation without coupling
  - Watcher monitors target's health
  - Target never learns about monitor
  - Multiple monitors per target OK
  end note
}

Container_Boundary(semantics, "Semantics: Handler Invocation") {
  Component(normal_exit, "Normal exit (Proc.stop())", "Outcome", "handler(null)\nProcessed successfully")

  Component(abnormal_exit, "Abnormal exit (crash)", "Outcome", "handler(lastError)\nUnhandled exception")

  note right
  **Handler Argument**

  null = target stopped gracefully
  non-null = the exception that crashed target

  Target's thread has already exited
  Handler runs on target's virtual thread context
  Handler must NOT block (used for short cleanup)
  end note
}

Container_Boundary(composition, "Composability") {
  note bottom
  ProcMonitor is fully composable with:

  **Supervisor**
  - Child can be monitored independently
  - Supervisor restarts child
  - Monitor fires on each crash+restart

  **ProcRegistry**
  - Monitor registered process
  - Monitor survives registry lookup

  **ProcLink**
  - Monitor and link orthogonal
  - Same process can be monitored + linked

  **EventManager**
  - Monitor can publish events
  - Decouple crash detection from handlers
  end note
}

Rel(api, implementation, "defines")
Rel(monitor_method, termination_flow, "implements")
Rel(demonitor_method, termination_flow, "stops")
Rel(vs_link, semantics, "contrasts")

note bottom of api
  **ProcMonitor is a utility class**
  - Static methods only
  - No global registry (unlike ProcRegistry)
  - Each monitor callback stored in Proc.terminationCallbacks
  - Safe to install multiple monitors on same target
  - Handler must be side-effect free (called during Proc shutdown)
end note

@enduml
